29 technology, management, and budget to update the searchable website
RMH S06106'26 (S-1) n52eu9

19
1 on a quarterly basis.
2 Sec. 212. Not later than 14 days after the release of the
3 executive budget recommendation, the department shall cooperate
4 with the state budget office to provide an annual report on
5 estimated state restricted fund balances, state restricted fund
6 projected revenues, and state restricted fund expenditures for the
7 previous 2 fiscal years. The report must be submitted to the
8 standard report recipients and to the chairpersons of the senate
9 and house appropriations committees.
10 Sec. 214. (1) Funds appropriated in part 1 must not be used to
11 restrict or impede a marginalized community's access to government
12 resources, programs, or facilities.
13 (2) From the funds appropriated in part 1, local governments
14 shall report any action or policy that attempts to restrict or
15 interfere with the duties of a local health officer.
16 Sec. 215. To the extent permissible under the management and
17 budget act, 1984 PA 431, MCL 18.1101 to 18.1594, the director of
18 each department or agency receiving appropriations in part 1 shall
19 take all reasonable steps to ensure geographically-disadvantaged
20 business enterprises compete for and perform contracts to provide
21 services or supplies, or both. The director shall strongly
22 encourage firms with which the department contracts to subcontract
23 with certified geographically-disadvantaged business enterprises
24 for services, supplies, or both. As used in this section,
25 "geographically-disadvantaged business enterprises" means that term
26 as defined in Executive Directive 2023-1.
27 Sec. 216. On a quarterly basis, the department or agency
28 receiving appropriations in part 1 shall report on the number of
29 full-time equated positions in pay status by civil service
RMH S06106'26 (S-1) n52eu9

20
1 classification, including a comparison by line item of the number
2 of full-time equated positions authorized from funds appropriated
3 in part 1 to the actual number of full-time equated positions
4 employed by the department at the end of the reporting period. The
5 report must be submitted to the senate and house appropriations
6 committees and to the standard report recipients.
7 Sec. 217. (1) The department shall maximize utilization of its
8 in-person state workforce. The department shall prioritize
9 occupancy utilization of office space for each division within the
10 department. Employees with job responsibilities that require the
11 employees to serve in their capacities outside of an office shall
12 be monitored each pay period to ensure all work hours reported on
13 the timesheet were actually worked.
14 (2) The department shall comply with requirements set by the
15 office of state employer to meet the in-person and vacancy rate
16 objectives outlined by the office of state employer.
17 (3) The department shall adhere to the rules and regulations
18 of civil service, which state that the standard biweekly work
19 period for a full-time employee in the classified service is the
20 equivalent of 80 hours of work. The department shall establish
21 policies and processes to ensure all employees are working their
22 jobs during agreed-upon business hours.
23 Sec. 219. The department shall receive and retain copies of
24 all reports funded from appropriations in part 1. The department
25 shall follow federal and state guidelines for short-term and long-
26 term retention of records. The department may electronically retain
27 copies of reports unless otherwise required by federal and state
28 law and guidelines.
29 Sec. 220. Not later than April 1, the department shall report
RMH S06106'26 (S-1) n52eu9

21
1 on each specific policy change made to implement a public act
2 affecting the department that took effect during the previous
3 calendar year. The report must include reference to the public act
4 that necessitates the policy change. The department shall submit
5 the report to the standard report recipients, to the senate and
6 house appropriations committees, and to the joint committee on
7 administrative rules.
8 Sec. 221. If the state administrative board, acting under
9 section 3 of 1921 PA 2, MCL 17.3, transfers funds from an amount
10 appropriated under part 1, the legislature may, by a concurrent
11 resolution adopted by a majority of the members elected to and
12 serving in each house, inter-transfer funds within part 1 for the
13 particular department, board, commission, officer, or institution.
14 Sec. 222. To the extent possible, the department shall not
15 expend appropriations in part 1 until all existing authorized work
16 project funds available for the same purposes are exhausted.
17 Sec. 223. The state budget director shall take steps to ensure
18 that all state fiscal recovery funds allocated to this state under
19 the American rescue plan act of 2021, Public Law 117-2, are
20 expended by December 31, 2026, as required by law. Any state fiscal
21 recovery funds that would otherwise lapse after September 30, 2026,
22 are automatically reappropriated for the same purpose as originally
23 authorized and available for expenditure through December 31, 2026,
24 and any subsequent financial close-out period.
25 Sec. 224. (1) The state budget director shall take steps to
26 ensure that all state fiscal recovery funds allocated to this state
27 under the American rescue plan act of 2021, Public Law 117-2, are
28 expended by December 31, 2026, as required by law. The state budget
29 director may reallocate appropriated funds for the purpose of fully
RMH S06106'26 (S-1) n52eu9

22
1 utilizing state fiscal recovery funds that are in jeopardy of not
2 meeting the expenditure deadline for reasons that may include, but
3 are not limited to, completed projects coming in under budget or
4 funds unable to be fully used by subrecipients. The state budget
5 director shall reallocate any of the funds reallocated under this
6 subsection to the programs or purposes specified in this section.
7 Any funds reallocated are unappropriated and immediately
8 reappropriated for the following purposes:
9 (a) To reclassify general fund/general purpose appropriations
10 for payroll and covered benefits for eligible public health and
11 safety employees at the department of corrections.
12 (b) To reclassify general fund/general purpose appropriations
13 for payroll and covered benefits for eligible public health and
14 safety employees at the department of state police.
15 (2) All applicable guidance, implementation, and reporting
16 provisions of the American rescue plan act of 2021, Public Law 117-
17 2, must be followed for state fiscal recovery funds reallocated and
18 reappropriated under subsection (1).
19 (3) The state budget director shall notify the senate and
20 house appropriations committees not later than 1 business day after
21 making any reallocations under subsection (1). The notification
22 must include the authorized program under which funds were
23 originally appropriated, the amount of the reallocation, the
24 program, or programs, or purpose, and the department to which the
25 funds are being reallocated under subsection (1), and the amount
26 reallocated to each program or purpose.
27 Sec. 225. The department must provide an annual report to the
28 standard report recipients detailing significant federal policy
29 changes that do, or are expected to significantly impact the
RMH S06106'26 (S-1) n52eu9

23
1 operations of the department, including reductions in federal
2 revenue or changes that are likely to lead to a reduction in the
3 department's ability to safeguard the health or welfare of the
4 public.
5 Sec. 226. (1) Not later than 30 days after the effective date
6 of this act, the house and senate shall provide to the state budget
7 office a jointly agreed-upon list of legislatively directed
8 spending items funded in part 1 as defined in 2025 PA 32 and 2025
9 PA 33. The list must include all information and documents
10 pertaining to the funded items as publicly disclosed in accordance
11 with 2025 PA 32 and 2025 PA 33.
12 (2) In accordance with section 364(4) of the management and
13 budget act, 1984 PA 431, MCL 18.1364, the department or agency
14 administering the grant shall post a report in a publicly
15 accessible location on its website beginning March 15 of the
16 current fiscal year. The department or agency shall update the
17 report and post an updated report not later than June 15 of the
18 current fiscal year and again not later than September 15 of the
19 current fiscal year. The department shall include in the report the
20 most comprehensive information the department has available at the
21 time of posting for grants awarded.
